---
title: "How to Build an Internal Admin Panel That Replaces Five Disconnected Tools"
date: "2023-04-05"
summary: "Build an internal admin panel that consolidates five tools into one. Reduce context switching and reclaim hours every week."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Admin Tools"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your operations team uses five tools to do one job. A customer lookup requires checking three systems. A status update requires switching twice. The tools are the problem.

An internal admin panel is a single interface that surfaces data from multiple systems. Not a replacement for those systems. A layer on top of them.

Implementing this structure effectively requires a systematic, three-step methodology:

Identify the [workflows](/process). What does the operations team do every day. Customer lookups. Status updates. Report generation. List the [workflows](/process).

Identify the data each workflow needs. The customer lookup needs data from the CRM, the support platform, and the billing system. The status update needs data from the project management tool and the CRM.

Build a single screen for each workflow. The customer lookup screen shows all three data sources. The status update screen shows the project and the customer. The team does not switch between tools. The panel brings the data to them.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we built an admin panel. The panel replaced five tools for the operations team's daily workflows. The context switching dropped by 70 percent. The time per task dropped 40 percent. The team handled 35 percent more volume without adding anyone.

The panel cost $28,000 to build. The annual value of recovered time was estimated at $55,000. The payback period was under six months.

The teams that accept disconnected tools are the ones that context switch all day. The teams that build admin panels are the ones that focus on the work.

Identify the workflows. Identify the data. Build the screens. The tools consolidate.
